ry advancements in physics, computers, chemistry, and biology and make a passionate case for continued investing in science to meet the global challenges of our time.Clean air and water, cures for intractable diseases, greener public transportation, cheaper and faster communication technologies—these are some of the rich opportunities awaiting venture capital investment today. Jamison and Waite focus on how early-stage companies specializing in commercializing transformative technologies based on deep science have been shunned by venture capitalists, and how the development of such companies have been hampered by structural changes in capital markets and government regulation over the past decade. The authors argue that reinvigorating science-based technological innovation is crucial to reactivating the economic dynamism that lifts living standards and fuels prosperity over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNew business enterpriseszUnited StatesxFinance. 0aScience and industryzUnited States. 0aVenture capitalzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Investments & Securities / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaite, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2017z9783110547740oZDB-23-DBV40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/jami1757240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover